Part 8

Reddy came to the house himself this time, not summoned to any boardroom, holding a folder he kept patting like it might run away from him.

Binay received him in the small sitting room off his bedroom, the one with the good chair reserved for guests, thinner now than even the board meeting had shown, but alert, sharp-eyed, waving off the nurse hovering nearby.

"Binay saab." Reddy sat, opened the folder, then seemed to forget it entirely and just spoke. "Seven hundred crore. That's what the liquor business was doing when your son took over the South push. This year, it's crossed fourteen hundred."

Binay's eyebrows lifted slightly. That was the whole of his reaction, and it seemed to satisfy Reddy more than a speech would have.

"South alone," Reddy continued, "six hundred crore, manufactured there, exported worldwide now. Nobody thought a first-time entrant would touch international distribution this fast. We're already scouting land for two more plants. If this holds, we touch ten thousand crore within five years."

"You were the one who called him a kid," Binay said, not unkindly, watching Reddy's face carefully.

"I was." Reddy didn't look away from it. "I'll say it again if I'm ever wrong about someone else. I was wrong about this one."

Vikram stood near the window through all of it, saying little, the way he'd learned to stand through most rooms that discussed him rather than spoke to him.

When Reddy rose to leave, he crossed the room and rested a hand briefly on Vikram's shoulder — not a handshake, not a speech, just a hand, there and gone, the kind of gesture older men give when they've run out of better ways to say something.

Vikram felt something loosen in his chest that he hadn't realized was tight.

---

He stood at the window a while after Reddy's car had pulled away, watching the gate close behind it, and found the warmth of the moment fading faster than he expected it to.

Fourteen hundred crore. Ten thousand crore in five years. Numbers that would have meant everything to him once, in a hostel room, imagining a life entirely different from this one.

He didn't feel nothing. He felt, honestly, something closer to a duty discharged than a dream fulfilled — the particular flatness of doing a thing well that was never quite his to want in the first place.

Liquor had been his father's calling, not his. He'd carried it forward because someone had to, because the alternative was letting Binay's life's work collapse under a diagnosis nobody could argue with anymore.

Somewhere underneath the fourteen hundred crore, a much smaller, much older thought kept surfacing, uninvited: *what would I have built, if I'd been building for myself instead of for him.*

He didn't know the answer yet.

He wasn't sure, standing at that window, that he was even supposed to be looking for one.
